  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"> Intermediate Decks</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">Under It All</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><table width='70' border='0' cellspacing='0' cellpadding='0'><tr><td background='/magination/gfx/5star.gif'><img src='/lotr/gfx/trans.gif' width='1' height='25'></td></tr></table><font size=1>(3.5)</font> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=28999">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347">Daniel "Dartax" Burke</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> How about trying to burrow without Tunnel Hyrens? If this deck holds true to form, it can work quite well, with a surprising twist of Urigant.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> May 26, 2003</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Magi:<br />
Myka<br />
(Starting: None)<br />
<br />
Emaal<br />
(Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(647)">Impact</a>)<br />
<br />
Celebrated Hero<br />
(Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(481)">Gogor</a>&#8217;s Spade)<br />
<br />
Creatures:<br />
Akkar x3<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(469)">Crystal <a href="javascript:card_browser(394)">Arboll</a></a> x3<br />
Granas x3<br />
Kier x2<br />
Ormalet x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(637)">Pylofuf</a> x2<br />
Trogovo x3<br />
Urigant x2<br />
<br />
Spells:<br />
Atekkia&#8217;s Gift x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(492)">Bottomless Pit</a> x2<br />
Crushing Fungus x3<br />
Gorgle&#8217;s Curse x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(783)">Hidden Door</a> x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(647)">Impact</a> x1<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(648)">Resonate</a> x2<br />
<br />
Relics:<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(488)">Digging Goggles</a> x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(481)">Gogor</a>&#8217;s Spade x1<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(484)">Strag</a>&#8217;s Claws x1<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(484)">Strag</a>&#8217;s Ring x1<br />
Tunneler&#8217;s Boots x1<br />
<br />
Total: 40 cards   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> For the longest time, I&#8217;ve claimed to be unable to make a working burrow deck. That was true, then. However, this deck has tested true against Weave/Naroom (with Garan), Kybar&#8217;s Teeth (with Urigant), and a Voice of the Storm deck (with the spell of the same name and a ton of dual region creatures). There are no Tunnel Hyrens in the deck (considered a staple of burrow), and no Ormagons. So, overall, I was surprised at how this deck has brutalized its opposition so far. Myka took out both the Weave/Naroom and Kybar&#8217;s deck on her own, and the Voice deck had to use Cataclysm to get past her and Emaal.<br />
<br />
So, what&#8217;s the strategy? Let me see if I can convey how the deck is supposed to work.<br />
<br />
Myka starts with a great ability to stall, if you need to. With her, you want to get Trogovo or Hidden Door. Trogovo will draw you the deck if left in play, and is the real reason there is no Ormagons. If your energize is reduced, it can be hard to get enough energy stored up. On the other hand, you can still put Evu to shame in card draw. If they dispose of the Trogovo, that&#8217;s fine. You get your energize back, and still have the cards to show for it. If you manage to start with Hidden Door, use it to fetch Digging Goggles and Gogor&#8217;s Spade.<br />
<br />
Hopefully, by the time you hit Emaal, you should have already pulled into a Trogovo. While Emaal doesn&#8217;t have Myka&#8217;s defense, her effect alone can make them wary. Basically, you play her much like Myka. You want a Trogovo or Hidden Door. However, you now have a energize of five if Trogovo is in play. This opens up more opportunities with the cards in the deck. You will still want Digging Goggles and any other relic that suits the situation. Though, if the opponent is on the offensive keeping your creatures beat up, use Strag&#8217;s Ring to burrow something of theirs. Unless I am mistaken, it says choose a creature, and nothing about it being one of your own.<br />
<br />
Celebrated Hero, alternate Gogor, is on the end for two reasons. One, you&#8217;ll get the Spade again if you managed to use it with a prior magi. Second, well, Emaal&#8217;s effect makes her better suited for the first or second magi. Like the other two magi, you&#8217;ll want the Trogovo, again. And, if the deck has stayed true to form, you&#8217;ll want Hidden Door as well since you&#8217;ll have recycled the deck a time or two. Since the deck tends to cycle fast, you should get the Digging Goggles fairly quickly. If not, try and use the creatures that don&#8217;t burrow as much as possible. Most of them are still good without it.<br />
<br />
Okay, just drawing a ton of cards won&#8217;t make the deck work.... Um, maybe it does.<br />
<br />
First, the crucial relic is Digging Goggles. The others are secondary, just there to help. Though, it is fun when a burrowed creature attacks, gains one, losses its limit of two, and gains one back (Strag&#8217;s Claws), or to add one energy to all your burrowed creatures at the end of the turn, and so forth. Mostly, I have really enjoyed burrowing the opposing creatures. I don&#8217;t always do that, but it is fun (Strag&#8217;s Ring).<br />
<br />
If the creature is big, Gorgle&#8217;s Curse works great. Add in that the creature can&#8217;t attack until your magi is defeated, and you basically stall them for a bit while you build your wall. If the creature is small, then Bottomless Pit works. Though, I like to use Crushing Fungus, again that stall feature fires off. Resonate only relics that are a threat, Rayje&#8217;s Sword/Belt, etc.. And Attekia&#8217;s Gift is for those creatures that refuse direct discard. It doesn&#8217;t hurt that it&#8217;ll put a one energy burrowed creature back in the hand (use Crystal Arboll otherwise).<br />
<br />
Okay, that leaves the strategy on creatures. If you haven&#8217;t figured it out already, Trogovo is key. It doesn&#8217;t need to stay in play long. Just draw some extra cards. Who knows, you might get a second Trogovo. However, never play two Trogovo out at the same time. The deck can work with an energize of four/five, but it is not really intended for anything less than that. Also, if they put a Nightmare Channel on one of your creatures, or theirs, use Attekia&#8217;s Gift.<br />
<br />
Akkar. Simply put, it&#8217;s a chance to recoup the lost energize from the Trogovo. As a bonus, it can act as half of the trigger for Kier (whether you need a Underneath/Kybar&#8217;s Teeth creature). Add in that loses two less energy in attacks, it makes a great addition to the deck all around.<br />
<br />
Urigant. Surprisingly effective. Definitely useful when I am burrowing their creatures with my relic. Usually, I don&#8217;t play this creature until I am in control of the field. With any other of my burrowed creatures, it burrows itself. And while it digs them up in attacks (except itself, which can be used to your advantage), the burrow will apply to spells and powers as normal.<br />
<br />
Kier. Self-burrowing creatures are certainly nice. You&#8217;ll need two other creatures in play to burrow this, and one of those has to be Kybar&#8217;s Teeth. Hopefully, by the time you play this, you should have control of the field. Combos with Urigant/Akkar nicely. Otherwise, play it as normal as an attacker to help you gain that control you need.<br />
<br />
Granas and Pylofuf should be self explanatory, as well as Crystal Arboll. Use the Ormalet to establish control against anything that&#8217;s not Underneath. Plus, Crystal Arboll can restore the energy you spent on its power.<br />
<br />
While you will stall a bit to build out the swarm of burrowed creatures (usually not all of them will be burrowed), the deck itself isn&#8217;t really intended to sit back and wait for it. Attack as needed. This is why several creatures don&#8217;t burrow right off the bat, and those invulnerable creatures are great. Mostly, it&#8217;s just in case you don&#8217;t get the Digging Goggles for a few turns. Once you have the goggles, switch to a burrow mode, and attack some more. It shouldn&#8217;t be hard to get most of the creatures to switch. After you&#8217;ve taken the offensive, there shouldn&#8217;t be any more need to burrow opposing creatures, so you can swing the ring over to burrowing whatever creature you have that isn&#8217;t self-burrowed (Akkar, Trogovo, etc.).<br />
<br />
Perhaps, if I had Tunnel Hyrens, I might have tried building a deck with them. However, I have beaten those Underneath decks so frequently that I am afraid I that the Tunnel Hyren really doesn&#8217;t sound that appealing. Hard to pull off, and full of weaknesses to be exploited. This deck has its weaknesses, too. That is to be sure. As I said at the beginning, Cataclysm enabled an opponent to go through my first two magi.<br />
<br />
Okay, traditionally, I have posted substitutions for the rares/limited cards in my decks here at the end. This time, it will be hard, since the deck relies on a few cards more than I would like. With much headache, I present the following possibilities.<br />
<br />
Emaal &#8211; Fossik<br />
Celebrated Hero &#8211; Gogor (Digging Goggles, Crystal Arboll)*<br />
Strag&#8217;s Ring &#8211; Muggum<br />
Tunneler&#8217;s Boots &#8211; Enrich<br />
Attekia&#8217;s Gift &#8211; Mudslide/Tunnel<br />
Gogor&#8217;s Spade &#8211; Syre<br />
Gorgle&#8217;s Curse &#8211; Mudslide/Aglow<br />
Granas &#8211; a third Pylofuf, a third Kier, and/or Cave Rudwot<br />
<br />
*I really didn&#8217;t want to choose a magi with energize five, because a Trogovo could really put the squeeze on whoever it was. However, Gogor works with burrow and pulls the Digging Goggles, a key relic for the deck. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/magination/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=28999"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=28999" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/magination/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></td></tr></table></td>
